    value: 문왕(文王)이 사냥 나갈 때에 꿈꾼 것을 점쳐서 강태공(姜太公)을 얻어 그의 힘으로 천하를 통일하였는데, 이 꿈을 말함.
english:
  title: 'Stele Inscription and Preface for the Shrine of Founder Taejo of Joseon: ''The Sage Who Embodies Benevolence and Cosmic Destiny, of Sagacious Conduct and Divine Martial Prowess'''
  author: Kwon Geun
  language: eng
  text: |-
    When Heaven favors the virtuous to open the way of governance, it must first manifest wonders as signs of the Mandate. In the age of Xia came the gift of the Black Jade; in Zhou came the auspicious dream confirmed by divination. From Han onward, each dynasty bore such marks—all bestowed by Heaven, never wrought by mortal scheme.

    When our Great Founder dwelt in obscurity, his merit and virtue already gleamed, and Heaven's mandate showed clear signs. In dreams a celestial being descended bearing a golden measure, saying: "You shall use this to set right the realm." Thus the Xia's jade and Zhou's dream find their echo in his fortune. There came too a mysterious visitor, offering a scroll discovered in stone crevices of Jiri Mountain, inscribed with words: "The wood-child shall restore the three Hans." When messengers went forth to greet him, he had already vanished. The Secret Records preserved in the Bureau of Astronomy contain an ancient diagram speaking of "when wood bears its child," and Joseon, known as the realm of Gojoseon, has been spoken of these thousand years—now at last confirmed. Truly does Heaven's guardianship over the virtuous bear witness.

    I humbly examine the genealogical records: the Li clan of Jeonju is a great family of old renown. An ancestor served in Silla; marrying a woman of noble lineage, his line prospered. Six generations hence came his descendant; thirteen generations brought the Great Founder's grandfather, who entered service to the Yuan and rose to command of a thousand soldiers. For four generations the family maintained its honors, each proving worthy. When Yuan's strength waned, the Great Founder's father served the Gongmin King of Goryeo. When barbarian raiders struck in the year Sinchuk, the king fled southward. Our ancestor led the counterattack, claiming first victory. The following year he routed the northern invaders; the year after drove back the usurper. The king's trust in him deepened; his ranks rose to general and minister. He moved among courts with ease, devoted himself to the classics, and his conduct never flagged. His capacity to serve the age, his love of life—these sprang from his inmost nature.

    When Gongmin passed, strangers seized the throne. Corrupt ministers wielded power, darkening the realm's governance. Pirate fleets ravaged the provinces. In the year Gyeongshin, our Great Founder triumphed at Yunbong, and the southeast knew peace. When Minister Choe Young sought to root out treachery in the year Musin, though his methods proved harsh, our ancestor preserved countless lives. Choe named him to high office and commanded him to lead troops into Liaodong. At Wihwa Island, our ancestor rallied the generals and wisely turned the banners back. As the troops reached shore, a great flood swept the island away—all marveled at the sight. Choe was removed; the esteemed scholar Yi Saek became chief minister.

    In those days corruption festered, madness flourished, and disaster loomed. Had not our Great Founder turned the tide, the nation would have perished. Yi Saek counseled: "Your deeds honor the Middle Kingdom, yet without an official journey to the imperial court, all remains uncertain." A date was set. Our ancestor chose his most capable son—the present sovereign—to accompany Saek to pay court. The High Emperor praised and sent them back.

    In autumn of Gisa, the Emperor censured that a foreign surname ruled Joseon. Our ancestor, with generals and ministers, established a prince of the Wang line to reign. With careful stewardship, private estates were abolished, superfluous offices eliminated, and the people rejoiced. Yet high merit breeds envy. Slanders multiplied, and doubt clouded the prince's mind. Our ancestor, seeing his position at its zenith, sought to retire but was denied. Falling ill during a western journey, the intrigues against him intensified. The present sovereign, perceiving the moment, swept away the conspiracies.

    In the autumn of the year Imsin, on the sixteenth day of the seventh month, the sovereign and fifty-one others—including ministers Pae Geuk-ryeom and Jo Jun—raised the standard of righteousness and proclaimed our ancestor king. Officials and elders, without prior counsel, moved as one. Hearing of this, our ancestor rose in alarm and demurred repeatedly, but reluctantly ascended. Without descending the palace steps, the state took form. Could this occur save through Heaven's grace upon virtue?

    Immediate word was sent to the Emperor. His edict came: "The three Hans have honored the Li house; the people know no war, each enjoys heaven's gift. This is the will of the throne." Later: "By what name shall this realm be called?" Our emissary reported, and the edict returned: "Joseon is a noble name; let it stand. Thus shall virtue nurture the people and blessings flow to ten thousand generations."

    Our Great Founder's renown and righteous deeds had reached the Emperor's ear and heart; thus when seeking approval, consent came swiftly. No chance meeting, surely.

    Three years later, in the year Gapsu, the Emperor demanded the heir apparent visit court. Our ancestor, knowing the present sovereign excelled in learning and wisdom above his brothers, sent him. The sovereign's words pleased the throne, he received high honor, and returned.

    That winter, the capital was established at Hanyang. Palaces rose, ancestral temples were built. Four generations of ancestors were honored: the Great Grandfather as King Mok with Lady Yi as Queen of Filial Piety; the Great-Uncle as King Ik with Lady Choi as Queen of Virtue; the Grandfather as King Do with Lady Park as Queen of Respect; the Father as King Hwan with Lady Choi as Queen of Grace. Rites and music were cultivated, sacrifices performed with reverence. Ranks and robes were ordered, hierarchies clarified. Schools were founded to nurture talent; stipends were generous to encourage worthiness. Justice was administered with clarity; magistrates chosen with care. Corrupt practices were swept away, and all affairs flourished. Pirates came to submit; all lands found peace.

    Our Great Founder's sublime virtue stands as one whom Heaven blessed with courage, wisdom, clarity, martial prowess, and magnificence.

    Yet the traitor Jeong Do-jeon, rebuked by the Emperor for offenses, plotted rebellion. In the eighth month of the year Mulin, seizing when our ancestor lay ill, he schemed to raise a younger illegitimate son to power. The sovereign, perceiving this with clarity, destroyed the conspiracy utterly. He petitioned to establish the rightful heir as crown prince.

    On the twenty-ninth day of the ninth month, as our ancestor's illness did not improve, he yielded the throne to the heir. The heir, lacking issue and noting that opening the nation and establishing its rites were the sovereign's achievement, appointed him crown prince. On the nineteenth day of the seventh month of Gyeongiin, the Great Founder was honored with the title "Sage Who Embodies Benevolence and Cosmic Destiny." In the eleventh month of that winter, the heir also yielded his throne to the present sovereign. An envoy was sent seeking imperial sanction.

    In the fourth month of the first year of Yongle, the Emperor sent an envoy bearing the imperial seal, investing our sovereign as king. Soon after, imperial scribes arrived bearing dragon robes and nine-tiered coronets—the sovereign's rank now equal to that of imperial princes. Our sovereign served both royal parents with utmost devotion and reverence.

    On the twenty-fourth day of the fifth month in the year Muwu of Yongle, our Great Founder departed, aged seventy-four, having reigned seven years and abstained from rule for eleven. Bow and sword were laid aside—alas, what sorrow! Our sovereign's mourning knew no bounds; he observed every rite of grief. With jade tablet and golden seal, he honored the Great Founder with the full title and established his tomb as Geoneowon. The tomb was completed on the ninth day of the ninth month.

    When word reached the Emperor, he ceased all business to grieve. He dispatched imperial emissaries bearing elaborate offerings. His words of praise declared: "The King was bright and good by nature, reverent toward Heaven, loyal to the greater realm, and caring toward his people. Our deep regard for his virtue moves us to restore the name Joseon. His merit and virtue surpass even the sage kings of old Joseon."

    The Emperor granted the honorific name "Kangheun" and bestowed unprecedented honors. Thus through the Great Founder's reverence toward Heaven and the present sovereign's filial devotion, both receiving and continuing the Heavenly mandate, they garnered aid from Heaven and earth, above and below. Truly, how great!

    I observe that throughout history, those who receive Heaven's mandate achieve great deeds and receive wondrous signs recorded in the annals, their glory endless. Now our Joseon rises with virtue and mandate that surpass antiquity. We shall inherit the throne and long life, establish broad foundations for generations to come, and endure with Heaven and Earth.

    I, Geun, having received the honor of this inscription, dare not spare effort in laying forth the Great Founder's splendor for ages yet unborn. Though my brush is humble and my words insufficient to capture such greatness, I humbly offer these verses:

    Heaven bore this people,
    Set over them their shepherd-king,
    To nurture and govern.
    The virtuous it loves and guards.
    Heaven speaks not in words,
    Yet its mandate shines clear.
    Xia received the black jade;
    Zhou's dream came true.
    Our Joseon, when founding,
    Was blessed by a divine being
    Who gave the golden measure.
    Heavenly seals were set long before;
    The mandate stood revealed.

    Goryeo's age had waned,
    Its ruler clouded, its minister cruel.
    In harvest season came the call to arms,
    Conflict rose 'gainst the great realm.
    Our ancestor held righteousness fast,
    Turned back the banner.
    Traitors faced their reckoning;
    Loyalty was heard on high.
    The Emperor's heart grew glad.
    The Mandate came to turn.
    The common folk pressed it forward.
    Great works were wrought,
    Yet merchants in their markets knew no tremor.

    The High Emperor of Ming looked on in wonder:
    "By your deed a realm is born;
    The people know no war,
    Each enjoys heaven's bounty."
    He then restored the ancient name—
    Joseon was reborn.

    Geography surveyed, the capital chosen
    North of the Han's great flow.
    Tiger-crouched and dragon-coiled,
    Royal essence gathered here.
    Palaces tower high;
    Ancestral halls stand majestic.
    Benevolence runs deep; the love of life abounds.
    Governance blooms; harmony prevails.
    Hundred measures are complete;
    Ten thousand blessings flow.

    Wearied from diligent rule,
    The sovereign passed to his rightful heir.
    The heir, to honor merit's claim,
    Yielded to the elder.
    Brother succeeds to brother's place.

    Our brilliant sovereign
    Sees in smallest signs the portent;
    Twice he quelled rebellion's threat.
    His blessings grow most firm.

    The founding and ordering of the realm—
    All the present sovereign's work.
    The great mandate cannot be refused;
    The sacred vessel is entrusted true.
    With utmost care he serves two thrones,
    More reverent still his faithfulness grows.
    Filial piety and fraternal love reach the divine;
    Heavenly favor deepens all the more.

    Facing the death of the Great Founder,
    Grief and longing shake the soul.
    The Emperor, hearing the news,
    Halt all affairs in sorrow.
    Sent envoys bearing solemn rites,
    Offered sacrifices rich and full,
    Raised his name with honored praise,
    Completed all the mourning rites.

    Heaven's succor stayed unwavering;
    Great blessings flow without end.
    Descendants shall number billion-fold;
    The ancestral line endures,
    Uniting with Heaven—infinite its span.
